\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f3\fs20\lang1025\loch\f3\fs20\lang1025 I've been doing a bit of thinking upon old and new subjects recently, talking with Gary, reading his MS, talking with Erik Mona, and generally exchanging tidbits here or there with Allan Grohe.\line \line In speaking with Gary and reading his MS I have been catapult
ed back to my days of adventuring in Greyhawk, in fact I feel excited again.\line \line In speaking with Erik Mona I sense in his words and actions that same Greyhawkian desire, a desire to relive the essence of those older campaign days, which we variously refer to
 as the Golden Days, the Pinnacle of D&D's success, or the good-ole-times.\line \line Gene Weigle, who has been absent for a while from these boards, once said that there was more Greyhawk in the Maze adventures than there was in anything named Greyhawk in its recen
t incarnation. So too, I will say, is there much Greyhawk, which was D&D, and in essence still is, in Gary's Zagyg's Castle MS, and then too in Dark Chateau.\line \line This has less to do with whether a product has the Greyhawk name, of course, and more to do with 
whether the components of such works define what is good gaming and good fantasy. In essence, whether they are enthralling and enjoyable instead of turgid and unimaginative.\line \line The first Greyhawk incarnation defined the game, with Gary and myself and others 
too who added their parts to it. You either captured the essence of D&D and moved with it as a creative work in progress or you were clueless.\line \line I admit to never really thinking about that back in the heyday, as it was all so new and moving so fast, not to 
distract one in a bad way, but in such a dynamic fashion that one was caught up in the wave and carried along, learning through a combination of experiences which you gathered in and digested when taking a breath, and no doubt partially through osmosis.\line \line T
here has been a long--very long--history involved in arriving at this point. That Gary and others are still here to enjoy this phase, which to me has a dynamic unto itself, just as if things had picked up again without missing a beat, is really a very grea
t thing. \line \line I wake up every day these days and type a few pages before I go to the real world job. Recently, I have thought about those of us in the past who did likewise. EGG, Dave Arneson, Frank Mentzer, the host of others who have laid the groundwork for
 this incredible industry. Yep. I'm getting real nostalgic these days. I even think I can smell it in the air, like it is a living thing. Strange.\line \line All I know is that Greyhawk is still alive, a great effect which at one time overwhelmed us all, Gary includ
ed, as he was but the first to be enchanted by it. And so too are the other realms, like Blackmoor, as that Castle and realm was the first I ever stepped foot into to play an FRP adventure in. But Greyhawk's my home; and in essence, Kalibruhn was a reflect
ion of that place, and everything I write is a reflection of Gary's ability to inspire us through his words, his DM\'92ing and his encouragements. D&D = Gary (and other veterans) = Greyhawk.\line \line I have to occasionally remind myself that without Gary's immense in
put none of this would exist, and then too he is still inputting more. It's a wonderful time we live in to see such changes and additions.\line \line Enough waxing nostalgic on my part. Just feeling real good about the present state of affairs. Times are way good th
ese days.  }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "http://piedpiperpublishing.yuku.com/topic/1971" }{\fldrslt \*\cs8\cf2\ul\ulc0\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033{\cf3\ul\ulc0\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f3\fs20\lang1025\loch\f3\fs20\lang1025 [RJK] http://piedpiperpublishing.yuku.com/topic/1971}}}}
