\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\cf0{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af1\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af1\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang1033\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f1\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0{\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f3\fs20\lang1025\loch\f3\fs20\lang1025 Before EGG codified the gods there was St. Cuthbert and the Blinding Light Faith and Norse Gods. We also had the Lovecraft stuff represented through the Elder Gods, though not many folks attached themselves to gods or made big deals out of them in the earl
y adventures. Robilar really only mentioned Odin once or twice; Mornard's Gronan as well as Ratners's Ayelerach both swore by Crom, but not much else. I suppose when GDg&H came out in 1976 is when folks started taking interest in this part of the game. Dem
i-humans not being prevalent as players, I can't really remember assigning such information to them. There was a false god sect--Roloc--in the city, the temple of the elder gods outside the city, but only the myths of Greek and Norse to really sustain the 
folks playing. Erac's cousin called on Zeus for succor, only to be ignored, as we all know, so that part of the game then was just not codified yet, though EGG was working on it (the 9), and I was giving it some views (Mandarin, Roloc, the Elder Gods). So.
.. I guess that dwarves and elves would have gravitated towards Norse gods, like Odin and Frey respectively.\line \line Of course my ideas about Greyhawk gods--or gods in general--for dwarves differ quite a bit from established norms, as I do see dwarves much more a
s a non-Tolkienish race as later presented in D&D and more as the earth spirits represented in Germanic/Icelandic mythology. My conception of world races differ greatly from the typical racial and geographical borders and norms established by most "Fantasy
 World" structures anyway. I am less into the idea settled and fully explored worlds than into the mysterious, young, unexplored, unknown and unquantifiable. That is, if there is one race known, that means (to me in creating worlds) that there should be tw
o or three more unknown. If there is 5,000 miles explored, then there should be 50,000 unexplored; if we know of 2 great wizards, there are 20 more we don't know of (and I am speaking of entire race knowledge pools, not single PCs or sage guilds, etc). My 
